Confluence does not feature that enable Administrator users to grant Anonymous with any of the Administrative privilege in Global Permission or Space Permission. However, the documentation on [Setting Up Public Access|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/setting-up-public-access-156.html] contradict this:

{quote}
We severely warn against giving anonymous users any administrative privileges, either within a space, or especially over the Confluence site. Giving administrative privileges to untrusted users may lead to a serious security compromise of your site.
{quote}

Confluence 6.0.1 introduces the option out-of-the-box for to copy a page including all child pages. There is an option to copy all of the attachments on those pages as well in the form of a checkbox that is selected by default: {{Attached files and images}}

Administrators of large Confluence environments have requested the option to un-select this checkbox by default as copying large page trees with a lot of attachments can quickly fill up disk space.

This suggestion is tangentially related to CONFSERVER-6415, which is a request to allow admins to set a max size limit to a space.

*Problem*

When using the JVM parameter -Dcrowd.polling.startdelay=$TimeValueDelay

Where $TimeValueDelay=\{\{=$(($(($(date \-d "$(date +04:30-24:00)" +%s)\-$(date +%s)))*1000))}}I

It appears the the Caesium scheduler ignores JVM parameters and instead will write values in the tables for the *job_id*  and *job_runner_key* from the tables in the queries below on startup.
{code:java}
select * from scheduler_clustered_jobs as job
where job.job_runner_key like '%DirectoryPollerManager%';{code}
{code:java}
select * from scheduler_run_details as run
where run.job_id like '%DirectoryPollerManager%';{code}
This causes Confluence to ignore a parameter where the JVM is configured to run the sync at a specific time and instead use the time the node started to run the jobs instead.

The only workaround is to run the delete queries *before* restarting the nodes in a DC cluster:
{code:java}
delete from scheduler_clustered_jobs where job_runner_key like '%DirectoryPollerManager%';

delete from scheduler_run_details where job_id like '%DirectoryPollerManager%';{code}
This will then allow the nodes to use the specified JVM parameter to run the sync job.

*Expected Behavior*

The values would be set to the previously set values and not need to be deleted

*Actual Behavior*

The parameters are being set to the *start time* of the nodes, so if it is started at 6:15 AM, the JVM parameter is completely ignored and the jobs run at 6:15 AM.

*Desired behavior*

The parameters should retain the previously configured JVM parameter on restart and not write startup times for those values. 

*Workaround*

Run the queries:
{code:java}
delete from scheduler_clustered_jobs where job_runner_key like '%DirectoryPollerManager%';

delete from scheduler_run_details where job_id like '%DirectoryPollerManager%';{code}
Then restart Confluence node(s).
